**Approach (3 parts: 1 Tier-1 code change + 2 data backfills):**

### Part 1 — Supersession-awareness in the audit (Tier-1 risk; feeds the live pre-push gate)
Add ONE preliminary pass over `git for-each-ref refs/etude/retros` collecting every
`refs.supersedes` value into a "superseded set" (mirror the existing `git cat-file -p
<ref>:manifest.json | python3 -c "...print(m.get('refs',{}).get('supersedes',''))"` pattern
already used at audit.sh:375-379). Compute it ONCE near the top of the batch section (after
the `local_sha`/`origin_sha` maps, before check (c)), keyed by the bare retro-id
(`refs/etude/retros/<id>` minus prefix, matching `supersedes` value format).
Then in checks **(c)**, **(f)**, and **(g)** — each of which loops
`while IFS= read -r retro_ref; do ...; done < <(git for-each-ref refs/etude/retros ...)` —
add an early `retro_short="${retro_ref#refs/etude/retros/}"; superseded set contains
$retro_short → continue` skip immediately after reading the manifest.
- **(f)** (audit.sh:440-535): skipping superseded refs means the 10 old cohort refs +
  (after re-tag, see Part 2) the 7 workflow refs no longer reach the pre-cutoff WARN; the
  NEW superseding refs are post-cutoff with valid sidecars → PASS. WARN cleared.
- **(g)** (audit.sh:576-689): skip superseded refs so the OLD B16 ref (which the inline
  `SUBJECT_CONSISTENCY_ALLOW` currently exempts) is no longer evaluated; the NEW B16 ref
  carries `bead.1=etude-nm6` so its title `(6j8/kig/nm6)` matches subject_values
  (audit.sh:664-668 already collects `bead.*`) → PASS without the allowlist.
- **(c)** (audit.sh:373-419): skip superseded refs when collecting `covered_file`.
  COVERAGE IS PRESERVED because each NEW superseding ref carries the SAME `subject_run.*`
  (e.g. 6j8/kig) — so the covered-id set is unchanged and `uncovered_count` does not move.
  This is the one correctness invariant to assert in tests (no double-count, no
  vanish-as-coverage). Confirmed: superseding ref subjects == old ref subjects.
- Keep the inline `SUBJECT_CONSISTENCY_ALLOW` array mechanism in place but REMOVE the
  `retro-cohort-etude-6j8-20260526T215942Z` entry (audit.sh:571) — its proper repair is
  this bead (the comment at :566-570 explicitly defers it here).
- The `bypass report` / allowlist FILE (`dogfood-completeness-allow.txt`) is unrelated to
  retro supersession; leave it untouched (the `etude-nm6` bypass there is for the bead's
  missing RUN ref, not the retro — keep it).

### Part 2 — Re-tag the 7 mis-tagged workflow retros (data; via supersede)
Each is a workflow-scope process retro wrongly tagged `cadence-retro`. Re-capture each via
`etude retro capture workflow --file <recovered-body> --trigger process-retro
--supersedes <old-id> --decision superseded --occurred-at <old created> [--message ...]`.
- **Recover each body faithfully** (no fabrication): `git cat-file -p <old-ref>:manifest.json`
  → find the `output.role=="retro"` stage's `output.path` → `git cat-file -p <old-ref>:<path>`
  → feed that verbatim as `--file -`.
- **No 7-key sidecar** for these. Rationale + acceptance's "explicit reason for body-only":
  they are NOT cadence retros (the 7-key sidecar is the *cadence* convention, docs/retro.md:106,
  retro-meta.example `retro_type:"cadence"`); re-tagged to `process-retro` they fall outside
  check (f) entirely (which only inspects `trigger==cadence-retro`). The body-only reason is
  recorded in the supersede `--message` ("re-tag: workflow process-retro, not cadence; was
  mis-tagged cadence-retro in original backfill"). The supersede + corrected trigger BOTH
  remove them from check (f); supersession-skip removes the old refs.

### Part 3 — Backfill 7-key sidecars for the 10 cohort cadence retros (data; via supersede)
For each of the 10 (094, 0rt, 2ku, 6j8/B16, 8hq.4, ojz, q87, quk, shd, x0r):
- Recover the body verbatim (same `git cat-file` body-recovery path as Part 2).
- **Author the 7-key sidecar FAITHFULLY FROM THE BODY** (the live B16 body already labels
  Trigger/Finding/Changes/What-worked/Landed/Remaining — these map directly):
  `retro_type:"cadence"`; `original_event_date` = the old ref's `created` date (e.g.
  `2026-05-26`); `failure_modes`/`root_causes`/`follow_up_beads`/`decisions`/
  `durable_changes` extracted from the body's existing Finding/root-cause/Changes/Remaining
  sections. Arrays may be empty where the body genuinely has nothing — NEVER invent content.
  Validate each against `scripts/retro-meta-cadence.example.json` shape (7 keys, correct types).
- Re-capture: `etude retro capture cohort --file <body> --meta-file <sidecar.json>
  --subject-run <each old subject> [--bead <each old bead>] --trigger cadence-retro
  --supersedes <old-id> --decision superseded --occurred-at <old created RFC3339>`.
  Pass the SAME `subject_run.*` (and any `bead.*`) the old ref had so check (c) coverage is
  preserved and check (g) still passes.
- **B16 specifically** (`retro-cohort-etude-6j8-20260526T215942Z`): its old subjects are
  `subject_run.1=etude-6j8, subject_run.2=etude-kig` but its body title claims `(6j8/kig/nm6)`
  — nm6 is missing from the manifest (the reason for the check (g) allowlist). Re-capture
  ADDING `--bead etude-nm6` so the new manifest contains nm6 → title matches → check (g)
  PASSES; then remove B16 from the inline `SUBJECT_CONSISTENCY_ALLOW` (Part 1).

### occurred_at decision (etude-8hq.2): YES, set it on every backfilled supersede
The superseding ref is CAPTURED now but the retro OCCURRED on 2026-05-26 (the old ref's
`created`). Set `--occurred-at <old ref created, RFC3339>` so `etude log` places it at its
real event time (docs/retro.md:84-87 explicitly says the backfill bead "should set both"
`--occurred-at` and `--meta-file`). The sidecar's `original_event_date` MUST mirror
`occurred_at`'s date (docs/retro.md:73-87). For the 7 workflow re-tags, set `--occurred-at`
too (no sidecar; just the core field) for consistent log ordering.

